Usage:

mcrl_open [mcrl-options] file[.tbf] [c-options] tool[.a|.o|.c] [tool-options]

Basically, this applies Caesar/open "tool" to mcrl "file.tbf".

here:
1) mcrl-options are passed to the mcrl-libraries
2) file[.tbf] contains an LPO generated by the mcrl-compiler
3) c-options are passed to the C-compiler
4) tool is any Caesar/open tool in .c, .a or .o format
5) tool-options are passed to the tool

ad 1)
-alt [rww|jitty|...] - specifies which rewriter is used
-confluent ctau      - applies confluence reduction, assuming ctau's are confluent
-any-other-options are simply passed

ad 4,5) Examples (non-exhaustive) include:

generator [-monitor] file.bcg	 	-- state space generation in bcg file
evaluator [-diag diag.bcg] prop.mcl	-- on-the-fly model checking
terminator                              -- search for deadlock (using bithashing)
simulator				-- simulate the LPO
xsimulator				-- simulate the LPO
ocis					-- simulate the LPO
exhibitor < input.seq                   -- search for traces

See the open/caesar reference manual for more open-caesar commands, or
look at http://www.inrialpes.fr/vasy/cadp (search for open/caesar). See
(man generator) (man simulator) etc. for more options to specific
ommands
